lection_clock_designs"},{"short_id":"tb3el5","created_at":"2026-07-13T22:21:08.852-05:00","title":"The git history command deserves more attention","url":"https://lalitm.com/post/git-history/","score":50,"flags":0,"comment_count":5,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"gnyeki","user_is_author":false,"tags":["vcs"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/tb3el5","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/tb3el5/git_history_command_deserves_more"},{"short_id":"xngweb","created_at":"2026-07-13T21:29:52.099-05:00","title":"From coder to curator","url":"https://staltz.com/from-coder-to-curator","score":6,"flags":2,"comment_count":0,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"nolan","user_is_author":false,"tags":["vibecoding"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/xngweb","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/xngweb/from_coder_curator"},{"short_id":"nszzsn","created_at":"2026-07-13T20:15:04.166-05:00","title":"fred: A text editor that uses C for everything","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xz5aPCRxsv4","score":11,"flags":0,"comment_count":6,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"linkdd","user_is_author":false,"tags":["c","programming","video"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/nszzsn","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/nszzsn/fred_text_editor_uses_c_for_everything"},{"short_id":"jvvfbe","created_at":"2026-07-13T20:00:53.512-05:00","title":"CSS-DOS — A computer made of CSS","url":"https://css-dos.ahmedamer.co.uk/","score":2,"flags":1,"comment_count":0,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"outervale","user_is_author":false,"tags":["css","vibecoding","web"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/jvvfbe","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/jvvfbe/css_dos_computer_made_css"},{"short_id":"rtegvw","created_at":"2026-07-13T18:43:15.762-05:00","title":"Estimating the heights of New Yorkers from their scuff marks","url":"https://blog.jse.li/posts/smith9street/","score":29,"flags":0,"comment_count":3,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"veggie","user_is_author":true,"tags":["visualization"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/rtegvw","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/rtegvw/estimating_heights_new_yorkers_from"},{"short_id":"v3avrp","created_at":"2026-07-13T16:43:24.477-05:00","title":"Should Libraries Log or Propagate Errors?","url":"","score":9,"flags":0,"comment_count":10,"description":"\u003cp\u003eMy assumption was always: Applications log (and err), libraries err.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eToday, I was \u003cem\u003eshocked\u003c/em\u003e to learn that various ecosystems love logging things in libraries (such that silencing those logs is even an important task). My view of logs has been around wide discrete events OR (for small scale personal things) writing errs in a file.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eI was particularly surprised to learn this was an important consideration of making Go's slog, since you can easily propagate and enrich errors... Why not just err (and handle them by e.g. adding to the log context then retrying)? Or pass extra details in the return package?\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eWhat workflows etc. make this desirable? All I've been able to think of is the ability to change the log level and silence random extra information.\u003c/p\u003e\n","description_plain":"My assumption was always: Applications log (and err), libraries err.\r\n\r\nToday, I was _shocked_ to learn that various ecosystems love logging things in libraries (such that silencing those logs is even an important task). My view of logs has been around wide discrete events OR (for small scale personal things) writing errs in a file.\r\n\r\nI was particularly surprised to learn this was an important consideration of making Go's slog, since you can easily propagate and enrich errors... Why not just err (and handle them by e.g. adding to the log context then retrying)? Or pass extra details in the return package?\r\n\r\nWhat workflows etc. make this desirable? All I've been able to think of is the ability to change the log level and silence random extra information.","submitter_user":"veqq","user_is_author":true,"tags":["ask","programming"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/v3avrp","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/v3avrp/should_libraries_log_propagate_errors"},{"short_id":"opbq6q","created_at":"2026-07-13T16:28:36.731-05:00","title":"Adding a second middleware broke our typescript types","url":"https://www.inngest.com/blog/adding-a-second-middleware-broke-our-typescript-types","score":2,"flags":0,"comment_count":0,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"Linell","user_is_author":true,"tags":["javascript","programming"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/opbq6q","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/opbq6q/adding_second_middleware_broke_our"}]